			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date>May 31. 1854</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd I. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I am in Re&#45;<lb/>&#45;ceipt of your Letter by <persName>Mr. Noah</persName>&#44; &#38;<lb/> with regards to the Occident delivery&#44;<lb/> I must say that it is not rightly ar&#45;<lb/>&#45;ranged yet.  I assure you I do all<lb/> in my power for you&#44; and ever more&#44;<lb/> than my Business extends me time&#44;<lb/> but the Post&#45;office is so a mismanaged<lb/> concern&#44; that if subscribers do not express&#45;<lb/>&#45;ly inquire for &#8220;Occident&#8221;&#44; and merely<lb/> for Papers&#44; they do not get them&#44; and as<lb/> People in <placeName>California</placeName> care not a very<lb/> great deal of reading the same&#44; with the<lb/> Exception of a fur&#44; they neglect also of<lb/> trying to get and to call for them.</p>
				<p>I have a few names of subscribers to<lb/> the Oc to give you&#44; <persName>Lewis Bras</persName>&#44; <persName>S. T.<lb/> Myer &#38; Co</persName>&#44; <persName>A. Hess &#38; Hamburger Bros.</persName>&#44;<lb/> I believe however I have rendered long ago<lb/> already the names of the two first mentioned&#44;<lb/> <persName>S. T. M &#38; Co</persName> and <persName>L Bros.</persName>  I enclose you<lb/> a draft on <persName>C. R. &#38; Co</persName> for &#36;50.00&#47;100&#44; I<lb/> meet with slow sale of Your Books&#44;<lb/> and I would advise you&#44; not to send</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>any more&#44; even around the Hora<add>&#63;</add>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The Emanu&#45;El Congregation have<lb/> held a meeting on the <date>18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of May</date><lb/> when the resignation of <persName>Mr. M. Barnett</persName><lb/> was accepted from Vice Presidency&#44;<lb/> and <persName>Mr. <hi rend="underline">A</hi>. <hi rend="underline">C</hi>. Labatt</persName> &#40;I believe <persName><hi rend="underline">A</hi>. <hi rend="underline">C</hi>. L.</persName><lb/> in correct&#44; it is at any Rate the old man&#41;<lb/> was elected to fill the vacancy.  Also<lb/> <persName>Mr. Chas Emanuel</persName> has tendered his Re<lb/>&#45;signation from the secretaryship&#44; and ac&#45;<lb/>&#45;cepted&#44; on account of his early intended<lb/> Departure for the states&#59; his Loss&#44; I<lb/> assure you will be severally felt in the<lb/> congregation&#44; as he was the principal<lb/> in the whole congregation&#44; who promated<add>&#63;</add> matters<lb/> and things with that zeal &#38; energy&#44; which<lb/> are so promising for the Future Prosperity<lb/> of the Congregation&#59; he has also labored<lb/> very diligently to work up the subscriptions<lb/> for building a synagogue&#44; and in short<lb/> has done an inestimable amount of<lb/> good for the whole congregation&#59; the con&#45;<lb/>&#45;gregation amounts to about 100 members&#44;<lb/> and there is now more Interest exhibited by<lb/> them&#44; than ever before&#59; it has contracted for</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>the Building of a Synagogue at &#36;19975&#44;<lb/> <del>toward which</del> which amt. has nearly been subscribed<lb/> to amounts of averaging about &#36;125&#8212;to &#36;150&#8212;<lb/> at bearing an Interest of 6&#37; pr. annum&#44;<lb/> whilst money is worth here in <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> 3&#37; pr. month.  But the trouble the con&#45;<lb/>&#45;gregation has now&#44; is to procure a<lb/> suitable Reader&#44; such as they would<lb/> like to have&#44; who would be able to de&#45;<lb/>&#45;liver an English as well as German<lb/> Discourse and in short a smart &#38;<lb/> learned man at a salary of &#36;3500&#8212;<lb/> which I do think&#44; as they seek a man&#44;<lb/> entirely to little for <placeName>California</placeName>&#59; however<lb/> I don&#39;t believe&#44; there is any to be<lb/> found in <placeName>America</placeName> not at <placeName>Europe</placeName>&#44; who<lb/> could get off their situations &#38; come<lb/> hither.  Married Jewish Families are<lb/> arriving with every steamer mostly&#44; to settle<lb/> here&#44; and we have quite a membership<add>&#63;</add><lb/> already.  I think I have never<lb/> furnished you since subjects to write<lb/> or say something about our <placeName>San Francisco</placeName><lb/> in your Occ.  I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Cauffman &#38; Meyer</persName></p>
			
